James, this is a once in a lifetime chance for a once in a lifetime experience.
 It's Cullough.
 It's nectar of the Gods, or God, whichever suits a man, I can't be bothered.
 It'll be monumental James, getting plastered with the finest scotch in
 the whole country, most definitely.
 So, what is the unhappy occassion of your visit here in uniform? Tell me
 all about it so I can forget it with the help of Loui and his wares.
 Did someone die? Are the Biafrans hurtling shells at Lagos? Did you concede
 defeat? Can I go home now?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The heavily set man, who otherwise seemed intimidating and capable of severely
 wounding a man armed with nothing but his hands, had a strangely calm and
 serene look in his face, as if he had suddenly drifted far away in his
 mind to a better place when he said calmly:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It's your brother.
 We have reports their caravan was probably attacked today.
 Somewhere in the jungle near the border.
 They never reached <TOWN>.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan looked suddenly somber and withdrawn.
 The news were a mood killer to say the least.
 He looked at James with wary, stern eyes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Well, what is the Army going to do about it? The Red Cross is supposed to
 have its support.
 Where's the support, James?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
James took Ethan by the arm and told him in a friendly, casual manner that
 his external appearance belied:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

We need to talk about a few things Ethan.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

