\begin_layout Standard
The Metropolitaine was in full swing.
 A small gang of sailors were celebrating one of their mates birthday, following
 the customary rule of drinking till the botswain comes looking for them.
 Loui kept a wary eye on a couple of strange figures, but other than that
 the orders kept coming in and that made him a happy man.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan on the other hand looked far from jovial.
 Indeed, news of losing contact with his brother had suddenly turned this
 war into a personal matter, something that every professional soldier tried
 to avoid.
 Making warfare personal made it a matter of sentiment, and that usually
 threw logic and reason out the window.
 It also meant someone would do something stupid, and stupidity was a well-known
 but also much overlooked factor in dying.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
James had fallen silent for a couple minutes, silently sipping at his wine,
 a local unbottled variety without a fancy name and year or an extravagant
 price.
 Ethan was down to his last couple of cigarettes, chain-smoking ever since
 they sat down to talk.
 At length, Ethan broke the uncomfortable silence:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I should have pulled some strings when he told me he was going in with the
 Red Cross.
 Red tape, paperwork, passport trouble.
 Surely someone you know in the Interior could have been of some help.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
James motioned a definite `no' with his head, eyes closed shut.
 He then had another sip before answering:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Do you honestly believe someone would be bothered with that? Not to mention
 that holding up a Red Cross caravan would be a publicity headache.
 Surely, the war in Nigeria is not as popular, or should I say as infamous,
 but people watch and criticise.
 We are trying to secure help and end this swiftly.
 That's one of the reasons you're here Ethan.
 What would the London times write? It's bad politics, Ethan.
 No need to add more to our bag of troubles.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan drew heavily on his cigarette and exhaled briskly, his slight irritation
 evident in his suddenly louder voice.
 He was now talking faster when he said:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Bag of troubles? You've barely become a state and it's all coming loose
 at the seams.
 There's probably hundreds if not thousands of people who come and go across
 your so-called borders as they please, people for which you haven't got
 the slightest idea, and you're trying to tell me that denying entry to
 one man in a Red Cross caravan would lose the war for you? I've heard shitty
 reasons before, but this outdoes even the shit of a rhino! I didn't even
 try James, and you're telling me you can't stop a man from entering?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
James was as calm as before, answering with a flat and emotionless voice,
 trying to calm down Ethan as well:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Not with a Red Cross caravan.
 They would have made official claims, told their story to the press, the
 press would tell the world Nigeria is performing a genocide, stampeding
 all over the Geneva convention and so on.
 They would have made us look like child killers.
 And you now our support in your parliament is thin, to say the least.
 No, we could not have told your brother to just go home.
 It was your job to do so if you wanted.
 Not mine, and certainly not Nigeria's.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan put out his cigarette, drank the rest of his drink in one go and motioned
 his empty glass to Loui who seemed to notice almost immediately.
 Ethan then looked straight into James' eyes, dark eyes which were accented
 by the small bit of white that surrounded them.
 He tried to calm himself and find the right words:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

You are right about that.
 It was my job.
 I should have just whipped him good like when we were still ten years old.
 But he's a grown man, a doctor.
 He has his duties, his obligations.
 Like I have mine.
 Though I still think it's stupid, at least he acted like the man he's supposed
 to be.
 He wanted to help, he signed up with the Red Cross.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There was a pause.
 Loui was returning to their table with Ethan's refill of Cullough, and
 a clean ashtray.
 Ethan took his time before continuing, and nodded his thanks to Loui who
 bowed slightly and fleeted off to serve some other corner in the Metropolitaine.
 James had rested his arms on the table, his frame and build too large to
 sit comfortably almost anywhere.
 Ethan took a mouthful of Cullough and flinched when he felt it burn down
 through his throat and into his stomach.
 He then went on:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

It's not just his job, it's his service to the world, treating the sick
 and the wounded.
 I know war's no place for idealists and romantics.
 I've seen it real up close and personal and I'd like none of that come
 knocking at my door.
 Maybe I even think Stanley's doing a better job than I ever could.
 Can't really tell why I didn't stop him.
 I just couldn't, you know? Dammit, why couldn't he just stay at home and
 sent food and medicine packages?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
James blinked languidly while sipping the last bit of his wine before replying:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Someone has to deliver those as well.
 Should they just drop them from a plane Ethan?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan's face grimaced his slight annoyance at the suggestion, and lit up
 one of the last cigarettes in his pack.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Well, I don't know.
 I'm not in the business of saving people, am I? You could say we're antagonists
, me and Stanley.
 At least, we used to be in different teams when we balled.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I didn't know you play cricket.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Haven't ever since the leg injury in Kenya.
 Nasty business that was.
 Almost got meself killed.
 Young, stupid and rush.
 Also, quite lucky.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
James expression seemed to change somewhat.
 He removed his hands from the table and for a moment sat still, looking
 at Ethan intensely.
 He then ordered another drink from Loui, who seemingly kept a watchful
 eye at their table more so than other tables and nodded promptly, going
 at the back for a couple minutes.
 When James spoke next, he was lighting up Ethan's last cigarette, receiving
 nothing but the stunned surprise and deep furrow of Ethan:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

What happened in Kenya that almost got you killed?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I thought you didn't smoke.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I'm a man of many talents.
 And vices.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Well, not a Rolling Stones fan as well I hope.
 It'd be a real crime to find you've been hiding that as well.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
James drew on his cigarette and threw his head back to let off the smoke.
 He was smiling when he pointed to Ethan and said:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Not much to hide, Ethan.
 Sometimes I smoke.
 Usually when I'm alone.
 Which is really very little time.
 Barely enough for a smoke.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan nodded with a sly grin on his face.
 He sipped another mouthful from his glass of scotch which was disappearing
 fast.
 James went on:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I didn't know you played cricket.
 I thought you were more like the football sort.
 Now that's a sport.
 What else is there I don't know about you.
 What about that nasty business in Kenya, was it?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan smiled while trying to down the last mouthful of Cullogh from his
 glass, and pointed to his mouth.
 When he did swallow it, his face contorted from the intense feeling of
 a wet fireball going down to his belly, but managed to respond timely:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Kenya, right.
 Nineteen sixty three.
 The yankees had just invaded Vietnam and my team had shipped out to Kenya
 as part of an operation to stall the guerillas, turn them on each other,
 make contact with loyalists, stop the insurrection in its infancy.
 It was pretty complex, and too damn ambitious with so few men.
 No small wonder it failed.
 And it wasn't because of that we lost Kenya.
 Anyway, that part of the story's known.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan stopped for a moment when Loui came with James' new glass of wine.
 He picked up Ethan's empty glass and nodded with a wink, before leaving
 them alone once again.
 Somewhere in the opposite corner of the Metropolitaine a loud crashing
 noise was heard and Ethans fleeting gaze revealed the bunch of sailors
 strewn around over lots of broken glasses and a couple of upturned tables.
 A loud chorus of laughters was heard and once the noise resumed its regularly
 high levels, Ethan decided to go on:
\end_layout

